<section id="eip-658"><title>Sincs and Rectangles</title><para id="eip-209">Another common CTFT pair has to do with sinc and rectangle functions. If <m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>

 is a rectangle function, then its CTFT <m:math>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>
 is a sinc (<link target-id="fig12"/>):<newline/>
<m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo>
  <m:mrow>
    <m:mo>{</m:mo>
    <m:mtable columnalign="left left" rowspacing=".2em" columnspacing="1em" displaystyle="false">
      <m:mtr>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
        </m:mtd>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mi>t</m:mi>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mo>≤</m:mo>
          <m:mi>T</m:mi>
        </m:mtd>
      </m:mtr>
      <m:mtr>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mn>0</m:mn>
        </m:mtd>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mi>t</m:mi>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mo>&gt;</m:mo>
          <m:mi>T</m:mi>
        </m:mtd>
      </m:mtr>
    </m:mtable>
    <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true" symmetric="true"/>
  </m:mrow>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">↔</m:mo>
  <m:mfrac>
    <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>2</m:mn>
      <m:mi>sin</m:mi>
      <m:mo>⁡</m:mo>
      <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
      <m:mi>T</m:mi>
      <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
      <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
    </m:mrow>
    <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  </m:mfrac>
</m:math>
<newline/>
Likewise, if it is
<m:math>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>
 that is a rectangle, then <m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>
 will be a sinc (<link target-id="fig13"/>):<newline/>
<m:math>
  <m:mfrac>
    <m:mrow>
      <m:mi>sin</m:mi>
      <m:mo>⁡</m:mo>
      <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
      <m:mi>W</m:mi>
      <m:mi>t</m:mi>
      <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
    </m:mrow>
    <m:mrow>
      <m:mi>π</m:mi>
      <m:mi>t</m:mi>
    </m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">↔</m:mo>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo>
  <m:mrow>
    <m:mo>{</m:mo>
    <m:mtable columnalign="left left" rowspacing=".2em" columnspacing="1em" displaystyle="false">
      <m:mtr>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
        </m:mtd>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mo>≤</m:mo>
          <m:mi>W</m:mi>
        </m:mtd>
      </m:mtr>
      <m:mtr>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mn>0</m:mn>
        </m:mtd>
        <m:mtd>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mo>&gt;</m:mo>
          <m:mi>W</m:mi>
        </m:mtd>
      </m:mtr>
    </m:mtable>
    <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true" symmetric="true"/>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>
<newline/>
Just as with deltas and sinusoids, rectangles in one CTFT domain correspond with sinc functions in the other.</para>


