</tgroup>
</table></section><section id="eip-928"><title>CTFT Time/Frequency Relationships</title><para id="eip-748">For a given CTFT pair, making a change to one side of the pair will of course influence the other (because a signal and its CTFT have a one-to-one relationship). We’ll now take a look at some of the ways a change in one domain corresponds to a change in the other.</para><section id="eip-790"><title>Time/Frequency Scaling</title><para id="eip-414">
Recall that a rectangle and sinc are a CTFT pair (<link target-id="fig14"/>). <link target-id="fig15"/> shows what happens when we double the time scale for <m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>. Notice how it halves the frequency scale for <m:math>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>. Then, as you might expect, <link target-id="fig16"/> shows what when we halve the time scale for <m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>, it doubles the frequency scale for <m:math>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>.</para>
