</table></section><section id="eip-487"><title>CTFT Preservation of Inner Product and Energy</title><para id="eip-212">Whereas most of the time/frequency properties we have considered have a reciprocal relationship, the final property is more of an identity. Suppose we have two continuous-time infinite length signals, <m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>
 and <m:math>
  <m:mi>g</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>, with corresponding CTFTs <m:math>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>
 and <m:math>
  <m:mi>G</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>. The inner product of the two signals is simply a scaled version of the inner product of their CTFTs (and vice versa):<newline/>
<m:math>
  <m:mtable columnalign="right left right left right left right left right left right left" rowspacing="3pt" columnspacing="0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle="true">
    <m:mtr>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟨</m:mo>
        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo>,</m:mo>
        <m:mi>g</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟩</m:mo>
      </m:mtd>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:mi/>
        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
        <m:mfrac>
          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
            <m:mi>π</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:mfrac>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟨</m:mo>
        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>j</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo>,</m:mo>
        <m:mi>G</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>j</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟩</m:mo>
      </m:mtd>
    </m:mtr>
    <m:mtr>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:msubsup>
          <m:mo>∫</m:mo>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo>−</m:mo>
            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:msubsup>
        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:msup>
          <m:mi>g</m:mi>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo>∗</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:msup>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mi>d</m:mi>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
      </m:mtd>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:mi/>
        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
        <m:mfrac>
          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
            <m:mi>π</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:mfrac>
        <m:msubsup>
          <m:mo>∫</m:mo>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo>−</m:mo>
            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:msubsup>
        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>j</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:msup>
          <m:mi>G</m:mi>
          <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <m:mo>∗</m:mo>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:msup>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>j</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mi>d</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
      </m:mtd>
    </m:mtr>
  </m:mtable>
</m:math>
<newline/>
This property is known as <term>Parseval's Theorem</term>, and it is pretty remarkable. The two signals look very different from their CTFTs, but their inner products are the same, simply scaled by <m:math>
  <m:mfrac>
    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
    <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>2</m:mn>
      <m:mi>π</m:mi>
    </m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>
</m:math>. This property might come in handy in cases where finding the inner product might be easier in one domain than the other.</para><para id="eip-448">It can also be used in another way, by making the two signals identical. In this case then we have:<newline/>
<m:math>
  <m:mtable columnalign="right left right left right left right left right left right left" rowspacing="3pt" columnspacing="0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle="true">
    <m:mtr>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟨</m:mo>
        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo>,</m:mo>
        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟩</m:mo>
      </m:mtd>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:mi/>
        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
        <m:mfrac>
          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
            <m:mi>π</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:mfrac>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟨</m:mo>
        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>j</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo>,</m:mo>
        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>j</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">⟩</m:mo>
      </m:mtd>
    </m:mtr>
    <m:mtr>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">∥</m:mo>
        <m:mi>x</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>t</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:msubsup>
          <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">∥</m:mo>
          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        </m:msubsup>
      </m:mtd>
      <m:mtd>
        <m:mi/>
        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
        <m:mfrac>
          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mn>2</m:mn>
            <m:mi>π</m:mi>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:mfrac>
        <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">∥</m:mo>
        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
        <m:mi>j</m:mi>
        <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
        <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
        <m:msubsup>
          <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">∥</m:mo>
          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
        </m:msubsup>
      </m:mtd>
    </m:mtr>
  </m:mtable>
</m:math><newline/>
This shows that the CTFT preserves the energy of a signal (with a <m:math>
  <m:mfrac>
    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
    <m:mrow>
      <m:mn>2</m:mn>
      <m:mi>π</m:mi>
    </m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>
</m:math>
 scaling factor), and is known as <term>Plancherel's Theorem</term>.</para></section><section id="eip-951"><title>CTFT Symmetry</title><para id="eip-922">Most of the CTFTs we have seen exhibit a kind of symmetry. Consider the <m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>
 and <m:math>
  <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
    <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
  </m:mrow>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
  <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
    <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>
 in <link target-id="fig21"/>. <m:math>
  <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
    <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
  </m:mrow>
  <m:mi>X</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>j</m:mi>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
  <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
    <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>
 is even, being symmetric about <m:math>
  <m:mi>ω</m:mi>
  <m:mo>=</m:mo>
  <m:mn>0</m:mn>
</m:math>, even though <m:math>
  <m:mi>x</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
  <m:mi>t</m:mi>
  <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
</m:math>
 did not have such symmetry.</para>
<figure id="fig21" orient="vertical"><subfigure id="fig21s1">
<media id="sampledctftm10" alt="">
